Mira, the archivist, handed Kael a drive. “The un-curated library. Audio files. The laughter track is… potent.”

Kael nodded. “We flood the channels. Not with a message, but with everything the algorithm filters out. The messy, the pointless, the beautiful.”

The horticulturist, an old woman named Elara, placed a small, soil-filled crate on a console. “Botanical stress signals,” she said. “Ultrasonic pulses from thirsty roots. Let the system try to parse that.”

The transmission was not an attack, but a gift. A donation of chaos. They began to broadcast.
In the control center, the alerts became a chorus.

